			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I will start with reply to your tweaking question. (I use the term twinking, same difference)
<br />

<br />
I am an Everquest veteran, since the game was released. I was hardcore for about 2yrs, now I am a humbled casual player. I hate tweaking as well, but guess what, if it was not for twinking I would have quit around the creation of my second character!
<br />

<br />
I personally would not tweak if the game was set up a bit differently, and this is where I can start typing about the future of Mmorpg’s. (I will not type about all my ideas, for I would type a book)
<br />

<br />
The most important area is <span style="font-weight: bold">character development</span>. 
<br />

<br />
I began twinking, because there was very little class separation in Everquest. As an example, melee classes receive the same skills, just at different levels, and skill caps. The only thing that separates characters in Everquest is gear, and level.  If one Rogue wanted to become a parry master, focusing on rapier weapons, they could not. If a Rogue wanted to focus on stealth and backstabbing, they could not. The only thing that separated Rogues within Everquest…you guessed it, their gear. 
<br />

<br />
To Everquest a rogue was a fighter with the ability to sneak, and backstab (they had more skills, but they were useless in the Everquest world). If the average Rogue had to tank a mob in Everquest, they could kiss their butt good bye. Players should have the ability to choose whether the rogue is purely melee or stealth. A rogue that focuses on parry and defensive abilities should be able to tank mobs as effectively as a Warrior, but the rogue built for stealth should not. 
<br />

<br />
The future of Mmorpg’s is to create dynamic characters, so it becomes next to impossible to run into a character “exactly” like yours. This would also eliminate one class becoming the dominant class/race combination. With dynamic characters, a vast, original, and dynamic world would fall into place behind them.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
